Hello,

When I execute the `makemessages` command, it seems to be unable to detect `trans` tags that have the `trimmed` option in it. e.g.:

```
{% trans trimmed %}
  #{{ invoice_count }} invoice
{% pluralize %}
  #{{ invoice_count }} invoices
{% endtrans %}
```

If I remove the `trimmed` it works:

```
{% trans trimmed %}
  #{{ invoice_count }} invoice
{% pluralize %}
  #{{ invoice_count }} invoices
{% endtrans %}
```

Due to some major limitations of the `pyjade` implementation (See: https://github.com/syrusakbary/pyjade/issues/285), I thought a potential workaround might be to use `django-jinja` and configure `pyjade` as an extension. This approach is warranted due to pyjade working flawlessly in the context of Flask.

However I have not been able to get it to render any `.jade` file. Instead the content of such file will always be displayed as mere text. I have also tried `pyjade`'s fork https://github.com/akubera/pypugjs without success.

Respective settings (using Django 2.0):
```py
from django_jinja.builtins import DEFAULT_EXTENSIONS

...

TEMPLATES = [
    {
        "BACKEND": "django_jinja.backend.Jinja2",
        "APP_DIRS": True,
        "OPTIONS": {
            "match_extension": ".jinja",  # also tried: .jade / .pug
            "extensions": DEFAULT_EXTENSIONS + [ 
             "pyjade.ext.jinja.PyJadeExtension"  # also tried: 'pypugjs.ext.jinja.PyPugJSExtension'
    ]
        }
    },
    {
        "BACKEND": "django.template.backends.django.DjangoTemplates",
        "DIRS": [],
        "APP_DIRS": True
    },
]
```

**Are there any suggestion what coudĺd be done to make `django-jinja` correctly use `pyjade` as an extension?**

