Sorry, again me :-) Using the default option ('match_extension': '.jinja') to discover Jinja2 templates sometimes fails, when also defining the Django default template engine (DTE) in settings.py. Here's a somewhat shortened configuration example:

The following configuration fails for _all_ Jinja templates, because the DTE is defined first - which results in _all_ templates being rendered with Django:

TEMPLATES = [
    {
        'BACKEND': 'django.template.backends.django.DjangoTemplates',
        'DIRS': [BASE_DIR+'/templates']
    },
    {
        'BACKEND': 'django_jinja.backend.Jinja2',
        'DIRS': [BASE_DIR+'/templates'],
        'APP_DIRS': True,
        'OPTIONS': { 'match_extension': '.jinja' }
    },
]

This one works:

TEMPLATES = [
    {
        'BACKEND': 'django_jinja.backend.Jinja2',
        'DIRS': [BASE_DIR+'/templates'],
        'APP_DIRS': True,
        'OPTIONS': { 'match_extension': '.jinja' }
    },
    {
        'BACKEND': 'django.template.backends.django.DjangoTemplates',
        'DIRS': [BASE_DIR+'/templates']
    },
]

However, in some rare cases, still the DTE tries to render a Jinja2 template. I wasn't able to track down the cause, but it's reproducible for certain views in my project (actually only one). Same problem with ("match_regex": "*.jinja$",). I assume the issues are related.
